flP. Sulpicio. P. Sulpicius Rufus was one of the greatest orators . of his day. His style was tragic in its intensity‚ his voice full and mellow, and his gesture and movements grateful and dignified: buthe lacked the wit of Crassus, whom he took for his model (Brut. 5 2033 cp. De Orat. 1, 5 27). At first he was regarded as one of the rising hopes of the aristocratical party, who smiled upon his candidature for the tribuneship (De Orat. Ι, 5 25). He is described by Velleius Pater· culus as ‘disertus acer, opibus, gratia, amicitiis, vigore ingenii atque animi celeberrimus) Bnt his talents and influence were lost to his party, when he obtained the tribuneship in lac. 88. For he flung him· self into the cause of the commons, and among other popular resolutioris proposed to transfer the command against Mithridates from Sulla to Marius It was these measures that led to Sulla’s march upon Rome, and to the first pitched battle within the walls of the city.
